body:
I did some research and found the root cause. Tauri uses wry to handle WebView stuff, and wry calls APIs exposed by [webview2-com](https://github.com/wravery/webview2-rs). The original interface of the WebView core, [`ICoreWebView2`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/webview2/reference/win32/icorewebview2?view=webview2-1.0.1462.37), does not support profile or preferred color scheme. This functionality is later added to the 13th updated interface, [`ICoreWebView2_13`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-edge/webview2/reference/win32/icorewebview2_13?view=webview2-1.0.1462.37). And to use it, one just [`cast`](https://docs.rs/windows/latest/windows/core/trait.Interface.html#method.cast) the `ICoreWebView2` instance to `ICoreWebView2_13`, and update the profile.

I did a local test, by adding the following line to wry
```
diff --git a/src/webview/webview2/mod.rs b/src/webview/webview2/mod.rs
index da3fb62..e247795 100644
--- a/src/webview/webview2/mod.rs
+++ b/src/webview/webview2/mod.rs
@@ -203,6 +203,8 @@ impl InnerWebView {
     let webview =
       unsafe { controller.CoreWebView2() }.map_err(webview2_com::Error::WindowsError)?;

+    unsafe { webview.cast::<ICoreWebView2_13>()?.Profile()?.SetPreferredColorScheme(COREWEBVIEW2_PREFERRED_COLOR_SCHEME_LIGHT)?; }
+
     // background color
     if !attributes.transparent {
       if let Some(background_color) = attributes.background_color {
```

and now my Tauri app will unconditionally use Light color scheme regardless of my Windows color settings.

It seems Tauri currently only sets [`theme`](https://docs.rs/tao/latest/tao/window/enum.Theme.html) in tao, and never passes the theme config to wry.
